\section{Introduction}

Effect size measures are an important part of modern psychological research. There are several effect sizes according to the type of data (e.g., numerical vs categorical) or the interpretation (e.g., standardized vs non-standardized). Beyond the statistical component of effect sizes measure, the ease of interpretation and communication is also a crucial part. When comparing two groups on a continuous response scale, researchers usually compute standardized mean difference (SDM) measures such as Cohen's $d$.

Despite the classical effect size measures such as the Cohen's $d$ or the Pearsons' correlation coefficient $\rho$ are extensively used, they often make strong parametric assumtions that are not always satisfied in psychological data.

% qui potrebbe essere utile qualcosa che fa vedere gli effect size in condizioni non favorevoli o anche
% il t-test lakens walsh che funziona meglio, cose così

Furthermore, despite effect sizes are mainly used for communicating results in an intuitive and standardized manner, not all measures are easy to understand and communicate. For example, Hanel and Mehler \cite{Hanel2019-hb} compared the subjective informativeness rating of several effect size measures. Cohen's $U_3$, a measure based on the overlapping between distributions, emerged as the most informative also above the commonly used Cohen's $d$. Cohen's $U_3$ is part of the overlapping family of effect sizes. This family contains measures that express the difference between two or more conditions as similarity (or dissimilarity) between the empirical distributions.

% qui qualcosina in più sulla overlapping family

We can divide the overlapping family into two main categories: parametric and non parametric measures. The parametric measures make some assumptions to calculate and intepret the overlap between distributions. In a similar way, the cohen's $d$ assume that groups comes from a normal distributions with homogeneous variance.

% qualcosa in più sulla questione parametrica

The parametric assumptions are relaxed for the other class of measures. In this case, the idea is to compare the empirical densities without assuming a certain underlying population-level distribution. A recent paper by Pastore and Calcagni \citep{Pastore2019-tq} proposed a general non-parametric index to estimate the overlapping between empirical distributions. The method is also implemented into an R package % cite the package here.
% something more about the previous paper here

