The aim the present work is assessing the performance of the overlapping index by Pastore and Calcagni with realistic empirical conditons where parametrric assumentions are not met and limited samples sizes create conditions where date are not normally distributed. % more here

\section{Simulation}

\subsection{Skew normal distribution}

To simulate different hypothetical scenarios we used the skew normal distribution. This distribution is very flexible because, generalize the normal distribution with parameters for the skenwsss. Under special conditions, the skew normal distirbutions is reduced to the normal distrinbyton. The other advantage is knowning the analytical form of the disrtirbution allowing to calculate and simulate the true population level parameyters for the simulation.


% more about the distribution here and formula
%% FIGURE --> plot with skew normal here

\comment{plot with skew normal here}

\subsection{simulation design}

We simulated a scenario comparing two independent groups on a continous dependent variable. Values for the first group are sampled from a skew normal distribution $y_{g1} \sim \mathcal{N} (0, 0, 1)$ and values of the second group are sampled from a skew-normal distribution $y_{g1} \sim \mathcal{N} (\delta,\omega, \alpha)$ % TODO check if parameters are described
For the population level effect size we used $\delta = [0, 0.05, 0.3, 0.6, 1]$ thus ranging from no effect to a high but plausible effect size and variance $\omega = [0.5, 1, 3, 5]$. Given that for the first group the variance is fixed to 1, the variance ratio is determined by the second group. Finally the skewness has values $\alpha = [0, 1, 5]$ ranging from no skewness (i.e., a symmetric normal distribution) to a relevant asymmetry. FInally we considered different sample sizes values $n = [10, 50, 100, 300, 500]$ thus from low sample size more common in experimental psychology and neuroscience and high but plausible sample sizes common in social psychology studies. % TODO vedi e ha senso questa ultima frase
For each combination of parameters ($5 x 5 x 4 x 3$) we repeated the simulation $n$ times. Then we calculated the effect sizes measure to be compared. In particular we computed:

\begin{itemize}
    \item $\eta$ that is the measure of overlapping developed by Pastore and Calcagni \cite{Pastore2019-tq}
    \item Cohen's $d$ with the small samples correction (i.e., the Hedges' $g$) \cite{Hedges1981-za}
    \item Cohen's $U_3$
    \item Common Language Effect Size (CLES)
    % here maybe worth adding the cohen's U_1/2 (with the criticism) and the non-parametric indexes (cliff delta, Kolmogorov, A etc.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{simulation analysis}

To assess the simulation results we caclulated three different metrics. The \textit{absolute mean bias} (AMB) that is computed as the average difference between the true value each iteration of the simulation. A value close to zero suggest that the estimator is working appropriately on the long run. The \textit{relative mean bias} that is computed by dividing the difference between the true and simulated value by the simulated value itself. Values between -0.1 and 0.1 are considered acceptable \cite{Smid2020-ut}. Finally the \textit{mean square error} (MSE) that is the variance of the estimates across the replications. A lower MSE suggests that the simulated values are closer to the true parameter. 

